data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code. Here's each one and the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` ŌĆö now takes `Func<>`, not `Expression<Func<>>`

Your manual expression tree construction **won't compile** because the overload now accepts a plain lambda. Replace the entire block with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda`, `Expression.Call`, etc. ŌĆö the condition goes directly in the lambda body.

---

### 2. Complex type column names ŌĆö now auto-uniquified & nested paths changed

Two related changes:

- **Same-name properties** across complex types (e.g. `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street`) now get a numeric suffix instead of silently sharing one column. This **will generate a migration that renames columns**.
- **Nested complex types** now use the full path: `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` maps to column `Payment_BillingAddress_City` instead of the old `BillingAddress_City`.

**Fix** ŌĆö pin the old column names explicitly if you have existing data:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, p =>
        p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});

// For nested complex types, pin each property:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

Then run `dotnet ef migrations add VerifyNoChanges` ŌĆö if the migration is empty, your column names are correct.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` ŌĆö new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter. Your implementation won't compile until you add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ŌåÉ new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (sensitive data redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for actual SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way. Use `logCommandText` in your log output ŌĆö it has constants redacted unless `EnableSensitiveDataLogging` is on.
